  "Used to produce the present tense": [
   {
    "text": "The participle can be used to produce the Hebrew and Aramaic present tense. ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "topLevelNodes": [
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "The present tense is produced by taking a pronoun like הוּא (",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "type": "italics",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "hu",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ]
       },
       {
        "text": ", \"he\") followed by a participle like כּוֹתֵב (",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "type": "italics",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "koseiv",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ]
       },
       {
        "text": ", \"writing\") i.e. \"he is writing.\"",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "There is no word equivalent to \"is\" in Hebrew and Aramaic, so it is implied by context.",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "A participle like כּוֹתֵב (",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "type": "italics",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "koseiv",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ]
       },
       {
        "text": ", \"writing\") alone is not necessarily in the present tense, and can be used in the past or future, as in \"he was writing.\"",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "The Hebrew and Aramaic \"present tense\" correspond to both the English present tense and participle",
        "type": "local",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "The Hebrew and Aramaic \"present tense\" correspond to both the English present tense and participle",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ],
        "targetSubtopic": "The Hebrew and Aramaic \"present tense\" correspond to both the English present tense and participle",
        "targetTopic": "Participle constructions",
        "enclosingTopic": "Participle constructions",
        "enclosingSubtopic": "Used to produce the present tense"
       },
       {
        "text": ".",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     }
    ],
    "type": "outline"
   }
  ],
  "The Hebrew and Aramaic \"present tense\" correspond to both the English present tense and participle": [
   {
    "text": "The Hebrew and Aramaic \"present tense\" construction corresponds to multiple English verb forms. ",
    "type": "text"
   },
   {
    "topLevelNodes": [
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "In English you can say \"he is writing\" (English participle) or \"he writes\" (English present tense.)",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "In Hebrew and Aramaic, both of these forms would be expressed with the same participle construction i.e. הוּא כּוֹתֵב (",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "type": "italics",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "hu koseiv",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ]
       },
       {
        "text": ".)",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     },
     {
      "ordinal": "-",
      "ordered": false,
      "tokensOfLine": [
       {
        "text": "Thus, when we see a sentence like הוּא כּוֹתֵב (",
        "type": "text"
       },
       {
        "type": "italics",
        "tokens": [
         {
          "text": "hu koseiv",
          "type": "text"
         }
        ]
       },
       {
        "text": "), we can't be sure from the sentence alone if it means \"he is writing\" or \"he writes.\"",
        "type": "text"
       }
      ],
      "children": []
     }
    ],
    "type": "outline"
   }
  ],
